WEBVTT

00:00.372 --> 00:01.374
Come on.

00:01.398 --> 00:03.164
Cook your signature dish.

00:03.453 --> 00:05.364
It's perfect for family dinner.
What is your problem?

00:05.388 --> 00:07.533
Sure. There's nothing better
than pitting family

00:07.557 --> 00:09.034
against one another in a contest

00:09.058 --> 00:11.270
to guarantee a stressless
and loving meal.

00:11.294 --> 00:12.905
Hey... whatever it takes
to get us all together,

00:12.929 --> 00:14.140
I'm down with that.
Thank you.

00:14.164 --> 00:15.441
Uh, and I think you will find

00:15.465 --> 00:17.143
my mandarin orange chicken miraculous.

00:17.167 --> 00:18.244
Mmm, thanks.
Do you want one?

00:18.268 --> 00:19.245
Dad!
Yes. She wants one.

00:19.269 --> 00:20.713
What?
We said no campaigning.

00:20.737 --> 00:23.249
Exactly. <font color="#80ffff">(COUGHING)</font>
Waffle potato pancakes.

00:23.273 --> 00:24.817
Hey...
Oh, thank you, that was very subtle.

00:24.841 --> 00:27.086
Waffle potato pancakes,
always Yukon Gold,

00:27.110 --> 00:29.955
always hand shredded.
And thank you.

00:29.979 --> 00:33.092
Thank you to my brilliant
and lovely sister

00:33.116 --> 00:37.496
for not cooking, so that we might
truly enjoy this meal. <font color="#80ffff">(CLAPPING)</font>

00:37.520 --> 00:38.509
<font color="#80ff80">HENRY:</font> Yes. Thank you.

00:38.533 --> 00:41.066
Well... it is my signature dish.
Thank you, thank you.

00:41.090 --> 00:43.035
Now dig in.
Okay.

00:43.059 --> 00:44.937
Um... c-can we say grace?

00:44.961 --> 00:46.672
Oh, we don't do that, sweetie.

00:46.696 --> 00:48.107
Well, why not?

00:48.131 --> 00:49.675
Yeah, we'll talk about it
at home, okay?

00:49.699 --> 00:51.444
It's fine with us.

00:51.468 --> 00:52.878
But not with the man
who never takes off

00:52.902 --> 00:54.380
his John 3:30 bracelet.

00:54.404 --> 00:57.316
Well, that's about faith.
And this is personal.

00:57.340 --> 00:59.151
I-I'm happy to talk about this later.

00:59.175 --> 01:00.519
I just don't think we should casually

01:00.543 --> 01:01.520
participate in a ritual

01:01.544 --> 01:03.088
we haven't defined for ourselves.

01:03.112 --> 01:04.690
Well, Annie casually
participated in saying grace

01:04.714 --> 01:06.692
at Gwendolyn's house,
and she liked it.

01:06.716 --> 01:09.462
This really isn't the time
or the place to discuss it.

01:09.486 --> 01:10.696
Exactly. So in the meantime,
if she wants to say

01:10.720 --> 01:12.131
a prayer and be thankful,
it wouldn't hurt anyone.

01:12.155 --> 01:13.132
And I think that this should

01:13.156 --> 01:15.234
be a family meeting for another time.

01:15.258 --> 01:18.337
What if the McCords say grace
and, Annie, you can join in?

01:18.361 --> 01:21.263
What if you two don't put
me on the spot like this?

01:23.900 --> 01:26.045
Mandarin chicken, anybody?

01:26.069 --> 01:27.580
I'm not campaigning, just asking.

01:27.604 --> 01:28.981
Do you remember the prayer
you said at Gwendolyn's house?

01:29.005 --> 01:31.050
Soph.
<font color="#80ff80">ANNIE:</font> Yeah.

01:31.074 --> 01:34.920
"God is great, God is good.
Let us thank him for this food."

01:34.944 --> 01:35.921
There we go. Amen.
Amen.

01:35.945 --> 01:38.090
Annie, do you want chicken?
Yes.

01:38.114 --> 01:39.032
Yum.

01:39.056 --> 01:41.427
<font color="#80ff80">HENRY:</font> Okay, what,
these-these are vegan, right?

01:41.451 --> 01:45.654
<font color="#80ffff">(PEN CLICKING)</font>

01:50.226 --> 01:51.504
I can't get past it.

01:51.528 --> 01:53.128
You should really try.

01:55.265 --> 01:57.343
Was it really such a big deal

01:57.367 --> 01:59.278
that his eight-year-old daughter
wanted to say

01:59.302 --> 02:00.779
a prayer before dinner?

02:00.803 --> 02:02.281
What, he can't participate

02:02.305 --> 02:04.850
in anything until he's defined it?

02:04.874 --> 02:06.485
What-what is that?
Babe, a lot of couples have struggles

02:06.509 --> 02:08.561
around the role religion is
gonna play in their lives.

02:08.585 --> 02:10.923
Yes, of course.
Remember us after Stevie was born?

02:10.947 --> 02:15.194
Yes, but the difference is,
you... are a sane person

02:15.218 --> 02:18.030
who is willing to listen
and respect the fact

02:18.054 --> 02:19.665
that your wife was
still working through

02:19.689 --> 02:23.369
some issues about organized religion.
Yes, and you were able

02:23.393 --> 02:24.837
to understand that it was
important to me to have the kids

02:24.861 --> 02:26.038
get some exposure to it.
Fine.

02:26.062 --> 02:29.842
Maybe Will and Sophie...
just haven't had that talk.

02:29.866 --> 02:32.011
Still... he couldn't
just do it for Annie?

02:32.035 --> 02:35.414
Have the-the big talk later?

02:35.438 --> 02:36.849
I don't know.

02:36.873 --> 02:40.152
You can't just put your kid
in the middle of a scene

02:40.176 --> 02:44.813
like that to defend some
vague... you know...

02:47.483 --> 02:48.984
...principle.

02:51.821 --> 02:54.400
So you're just deliberately
not getting involved.

02:54.424 --> 02:57.703
Bingo.

02:57.727 --> 03:00.806
Because you think that I'm-I'm
too parental with Will?

03:00.830 --> 03:02.708
Correct.

03:02.732 --> 03:05.744
Well, I was, actually...

03:05.768 --> 03:10.749
sort of like his parent.
And I feel a responsibility

03:10.773 --> 03:13.052
to help when he...

03:13.076 --> 03:14.075
does these things that are...

03:14.099 --> 03:15.487
Yeah, but then you just
talk in that tone of voice,

03:15.511 --> 03:17.056
and he gets angry and defensive,

03:17.080 --> 03:20.215
and he can't take in a word you say.
...so extraordinarily stupid.

03:28.791 --> 03:30.102
Maybe you should talk to him.

03:30.126 --> 03:33.939
Uh, no.
He respects you.

03:33.963 --> 03:37.610
You could give him
some... religious advice.

03:37.634 --> 03:39.845
Babe, he's a grown man.
It would be a perfect time for you

03:39.869 --> 03:41.780
to trot out your old pal Aquinas.

03:41.804 --> 03:44.016
I'm not gonna talk to him
about his adult behavior.

03:44.040 --> 03:45.017
It wasn't all that adult.

03:45.041 --> 03:47.820
Stop it.

03:47.844 --> 03:51.690
Look... you're going away tomorrow.

03:51.714 --> 03:54.393
Why don't you join me in this bed

03:54.417 --> 03:57.452
and we can not talk about it?

03:59.122 --> 04:00.633
Okay.

04:00.657 --> 04:02.691
<font color="#80ffff">(MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)</font>

04:05.995 --> 04:08.107
You move that State Department
folder one more time,

04:08.131 --> 04:09.775
and I will turn your stay
on the seventh floor

04:09.799 --> 04:14.046
into a horrifying fever dream.

04:14.070 --> 04:15.403
Thank you.

04:16.539 --> 04:17.850
You'd think the Defense
Department would be

04:17.874 --> 04:19.351
a little more secure.
<font color="#80ffff">(CHUCKLES)</font>

04:19.375 --> 04:21.353
You know what? I'm
actually kind of relieved

04:21.377 --> 04:23.422
I don't have to go to
Afghanistan with this crowd.

04:23.446 --> 04:25.557
The signing of the Afghanistan
Rebuild-Renew Agreement

04:25.581 --> 04:27.333
would be the event of the
year if we can pull it off.

04:27.357 --> 04:30.562
Hey! Leave it! Thank you.

04:30.586 --> 04:32.231
You're right. It could get tense.

04:32.255 --> 04:33.866
<font color="#80ffff">(CHUCKLES)</font> Still got a lot
of details to work out

04:33.890 --> 04:36.035
with President Sharza
about the spending

04:36.059 --> 04:38.937
of this $10 billion aid
package we're sending them.

04:38.961 --> 04:40.973
Yeah, well, they've done
everything they promised

04:40.997 --> 04:42.841
in terms of meeting
their human rights benchmarks

04:42.865 --> 04:44.510
and allowing the Taliban
to be a part of the government.

04:44.534 --> 04:46.045
So, they'll be tough,
but it'll work out,

04:46.069 --> 04:47.780
because it's $10 billion
and they need it.

04:47.804 --> 04:49.548
And Gordon Becker
will get that drawdown

04:49.572 --> 04:51.784
on close to 90,000 troops.

04:51.808 --> 04:54.253
Still no women allowed
in government, though.

04:54.277 --> 04:57.823
That must have been a hard
concession for M-Sec to make.

04:57.847 --> 04:59.391
You have no idea. Majority of Afghans

04:59.415 --> 05:00.826
wanted the Taliban
involved in the government,

05:00.850 --> 05:02.661
and they weren't willing
to budge on that.

05:02.685 --> 05:05.064
Oh, well. Just give 'em
another hundred years or so.

05:05.088 --> 05:06.465
<font color="#80ffff">(SIGHS)</font>
Oh!

05:06.489 --> 05:09.368
Hey, someone's a little
overeager for the trip.

05:09.392 --> 05:13.305
Okay, okay. I-I got that thing
for my mom first, remember?

05:13.329 --> 05:15.240
I'm arriving in Kabul a day late.

05:15.264 --> 05:16.308
Oh, right.
<font color="#80ff80">KAT:</font> What thing?

05:16.332 --> 05:17.843
Her 70th birthday.

05:17.867 --> 05:19.178
Oh, that's quite a thing.

05:19.202 --> 05:21.213
Yeah, her mosque is
throwing her a party,

05:21.237 --> 05:22.715
and I'm her surprise gift.

05:22.739 --> 05:26.318
Oh. <font color="#80ffff">(LAUGHS)</font> But you're also arriving

05:26.342 --> 05:27.553
with a real gift for her, right?

05:27.577 --> 05:30.556
Of course he is. His one
and only mother is turning 70.

05:30.580 --> 05:32.157
Okay. I've got to write
M-Sec's remarks

05:32.181 --> 05:35.828
for the signing in Kabul.
I'm only one man.

05:35.852 --> 05:39.832
Remarks for Kabul, useless
unappreciated gift for Mom...

05:39.856 --> 05:40.999
see what I'm saying?

05:41.023 --> 05:42.401
Well, maybe don't go
with something so useless.

05:42.425 --> 05:44.203
Or maybe just wait
for another birthday.

05:44.227 --> 05:45.604
I mean, she's probably
gonna live forever, right?

05:45.628 --> 05:47.439
Damn it. Okay,
I-I'll get the work done,

05:47.463 --> 05:48.807
and then I'll pick up a gift
at the airport.

05:48.831 --> 05:50.175
Hey...
Oh, yeah.

05:50.199 --> 05:51.677
'Cause nothing screams "thank
you for giving me life"

05:51.701 --> 05:53.078
like something from the airport.

05:53.102 --> 05:54.813
Jewelry!

05:54.837 --> 05:57.082
They sell jewelry at the airport.

05:57.106 --> 06:01.487
<font color="#80ff80">NINA:</font> Wow... how did this happen?

06:01.511 --> 06:04.623
Ah! You did this, didn't you?

06:04.647 --> 06:06.391
No. It's not my job anymore.

06:06.415 --> 06:08.360
This is Secretary of Defense Becker

06:08.384 --> 06:10.763
putting out a big spread
as a power move.

06:10.787 --> 06:12.631
Good luck with that. He's on our turf.

06:12.655 --> 06:15.200
Yeah, our turf, but now
we're all gonna talk

06:15.224 --> 06:18.036
about the food and who supplied it.
Genius.

06:18.060 --> 06:20.639
Yeah. It's gonna leave
a pretty big mess to clean up.

06:20.663 --> 06:23.208
I'll manage. So, wait, you were a part

06:23.232 --> 06:25.144
of this Afghan deal from
the beginning, right?

06:25.168 --> 06:28.447
Is it weird not to be
going on this trip?

06:28.471 --> 06:30.182
No. I mean, policy keeps me
pretty busy.

06:30.206 --> 06:31.750
Not too busy to remember to ask you

06:31.774 --> 06:35.621
if you set up a lunch date
in Kabul for the secretary

06:35.645 --> 06:37.256
and Amina Salah.

06:37.280 --> 06:41.326
Amina Salah... the former
Afghan minister of education,

06:41.350 --> 06:43.028
who lost her job in the peace deal

06:43.052 --> 06:44.596
that Secretary McCord championed?

06:44.620 --> 06:46.165
Yeah. Lunch is confirmed for Tuesday.

06:46.189 --> 06:47.800
Okay, now you're just showing off.
Yep.

06:47.824 --> 06:50.068
Okay, everyone. Fill your plates
and find your seats.

06:50.092 --> 06:53.238
And we can thank
Secretary Becker when he arrives

06:53.262 --> 06:55.040
for this generous spread.

06:55.064 --> 06:57.009
I-I... Gordon, I hear you.

06:57.033 --> 06:58.544
But there's been relative peace

06:58.568 --> 07:00.245
in Afghanistan for over a year,

07:00.269 --> 07:03.081
and contrary to our biggest concerns,

07:03.105 --> 07:05.250
Taliban has not taken
over the government.

07:05.274 --> 07:06.351
Then you haven't heard me.

07:06.375 --> 07:07.619
'Cause the hardliners
are already pushing back

07:07.643 --> 07:09.354
on the conditions we put on 'em

07:09.378 --> 07:12.624
to receive the aid package.
They're not gonna leave $10 billion

07:12.648 --> 07:14.326
sitting on the table.

07:14.350 --> 07:15.861
This is last-minute posturing.

07:15.885 --> 07:17.963
Look, I can admit,
the deal's turned out

07:17.987 --> 07:19.097
better than I expected,

07:19.121 --> 07:21.333
but it's a fragile peace.
I know.

07:21.357 --> 07:22.334
We've lost some good people

07:22.358 --> 07:24.036
to green-on-blue attacks.

07:24.060 --> 07:26.438
Well, we've lost far fewer soldiers

07:26.462 --> 07:27.873
than an all-out military attack

07:27.897 --> 07:29.508
would have cost us.
I-I know that.

07:29.532 --> 07:31.577
I-I understand the
benefits, Elizabeth.

07:31.601 --> 07:33.378
Believe me, I'm on
the side of the deal.

07:33.402 --> 07:35.081
Nobody wants the troops
home more than I do.

07:35.082 --> 07:35.963
I know.

07:35.964 --> 07:38.517
It's just my job to
anticipate the problems.

07:38.541 --> 07:41.019
And you're very good at it.

07:41.043 --> 07:42.354
Hoping that this briefing

07:42.378 --> 07:44.012
maybe puts some of
your concerns to rest.

07:45.014 --> 07:48.994
Wow. Where'd this come from?

07:49.018 --> 07:51.052
People got to eat.

07:53.556 --> 07:56.435
<font color="#80ff80">MATT:</font> There's so many pretty colors.

07:56.459 --> 07:58.537
I agree.

07:58.561 --> 08:01.356
It was hard to choose which ones.
Hmm.

08:01.380 --> 08:03.976
I love crafts, I just never
seem to have the time.

08:04.000 --> 08:05.477
Me, too.

08:05.501 --> 08:07.679
I was in the hospital for four months,

08:07.703 --> 08:10.816
so I had time to sew this.
Uh, well, not sew.

08:10.840 --> 08:12.718
That's, um, that's with a needle.

08:12.742 --> 08:16.989
Uh... <font color="#80ffff">(SPEAKS PASHTO)</font>
you, um, you braided them.

08:17.013 --> 08:19.124
Uh... yes. Braided.

08:19.148 --> 08:22.494
Well, whatever you
did, they're amazing.

08:22.518 --> 08:23.762
And your heart's all better now?

08:23.786 --> 08:26.899
<font color="#80ffff">(SPEAKS PASHTO)</font>

08:26.923 --> 08:28.100
All better.

08:28.124 --> 08:31.069
Ah. Yes. All better.

08:31.093 --> 08:33.138
Mm-hmm. Farhana will be able to lead

08:33.162 --> 08:34.438
a normal life.

08:34.462 --> 08:36.207
I'm s... I'm... I'm her chaperone.

08:36.232 --> 08:37.743
I'm with an organization
called Heart Train.

08:37.767 --> 08:39.311
Oh, I know Heart Train.
Do you?

08:39.335 --> 08:40.979
Yeah, you guys do amazing work

08:41.003 --> 08:42.114
bringing children to the U.S.

08:42.138 --> 08:43.649
for cardiology procedures.

08:43.673 --> 08:46.184
Mm-hmm.
Uh, actually, I gave you

08:46.208 --> 08:47.252
a shout-out last year,

08:47.276 --> 08:48.587
in one of the secretary's speeches.

08:48.611 --> 08:50.856
That's on our website.
Really?

08:50.880 --> 08:51.890
Yes.
Ah.

08:51.914 --> 08:53.492
We... Really, that meant so much to us

08:53.516 --> 08:54.493
to have the Secretary of State

08:54.517 --> 08:55.494
highlight our work.

08:55.518 --> 08:57.062
Good.

08:57.086 --> 08:58.397
I...
Highlight?

08:58.421 --> 09:01.600
Oh, um...
It's like, um...

09:01.624 --> 09:04.069
when you shine a light on something,

09:04.093 --> 09:05.237
to see it.

09:05.261 --> 09:08.407
Except you... we use words.

09:08.431 --> 09:11.076
Oh, I say "we" because, um,

09:11.100 --> 09:13.145
I write all the secretary's speeches.

09:13.169 --> 09:16.949
So many ways to say one thing.

09:16.973 --> 09:19.785
I'm very happy I got to come
here for my heart.

09:19.809 --> 09:23.288
But I find the United States too much.

09:23.312 --> 09:25.424
And I miss my family.

09:25.448 --> 09:26.425
Well, you're going back

09:26.449 --> 09:29.061
to Afghanistan healthy.

09:29.085 --> 09:31.586
And you've learned a new language.

09:32.588 --> 09:35.534
I'm afraid I will forget.

09:35.558 --> 09:38.003
No one in my village talks English.

09:38.027 --> 09:39.538
But I can't wait to be home.

09:39.562 --> 09:41.373
And have my mother make her piti.

09:41.397 --> 09:44.076
The bean soup?

09:44.100 --> 09:45.610
I love piti.

09:45.634 --> 09:47.769
My <i>Ade</i> makes the best.

09:49.772 --> 09:52.250
Um... excuse me. Sir? Hi.

09:52.274 --> 09:54.040
Hi. Hi.
Hi.

09:54.518 --> 09:56.788
I was wondering if you could
open this window shade.

09:56.812 --> 09:58.724
Um, I need some natural light
for my selfie

09:58.748 --> 10:00.192
or my skin looks blah.

10:00.216 --> 10:02.083
Okay.

10:04.887 --> 10:08.066
Yeah? Okay.

10:08.090 --> 10:10.024
Kids these days.

10:12.928 --> 10:15.073
<font color="#80ffff">(GASPS)</font> Oh, oh, n...
don't worry about it,

10:15.097 --> 10:16.108
don't worry about it, it's just, uh,

10:16.132 --> 10:18.377
a little turbulence.

10:18.401 --> 10:21.013
I hate turbulence, too.

10:21.037 --> 10:23.671
This is only the second time I fly.

10:25.574 --> 10:29.310
Well, I promise you, you'll be fine.

10:37.720 --> 10:39.097
Well...
That's perfect.

10:39.121 --> 10:40.165
<font color="#80ffff">(GRUNTS)</font>
I'm sorry.

10:40.189 --> 10:42.034
Uh, it was lovely meeting you both.

10:42.058 --> 10:44.469
And I-I really do, uh,

10:44.493 --> 10:46.705
appreciate the work your
organization does, Leslie.

10:46.729 --> 10:48.840
Oh, thank you so much.
Yeah. Come visit us sometime.

10:48.864 --> 10:50.108
<font color="#80ffff">(LAUGHING)</font> All right.

10:50.132 --> 10:54.079
I wish you good health
and a delicious piti.

10:54.103 --> 10:57.382
<font color="#80ffff">(SPEAKS PASHTO)</font> Mr. Mahoney.

10:57.406 --> 10:58.884
I want to give you this.

10:58.908 --> 11:00.719
To remember me.

11:00.743 --> 11:02.254
You can put it on your backpack

11:02.278 --> 11:04.089
or give it to your wife.

11:04.113 --> 11:06.725
Wow. Really?

11:06.749 --> 11:09.528
This is... This is great.

11:09.552 --> 11:10.529
I-I'm not married,

11:10.553 --> 11:11.797
but my girlfriend will love it.

11:11.821 --> 11:14.232
Thank you. I mean...

11:14.256 --> 11:16.034
<font color="#80ffff">(SPEAKS PASHTO)</font>

11:16.058 --> 11:17.836
You guys, the line's moving.

11:17.860 --> 11:20.328
Oh, please go ahead.

11:22.000 --> 11:28.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

11:30.539 --> 11:32.851
<font color="#80ff80">SHARZA:</font> <i>This timetable
for the rebuilding of schools</i>

11:32.875 --> 11:34.019
<i>is impossible.</i>

11:34.043 --> 11:36.288
Well, Mr. President, you have lamented

11:36.312 --> 11:39.524
on more than one occasion
that the destruction

11:39.548 --> 11:42.461
of the schools has been crippling

11:42.485 --> 11:46.264
to your next generation
and future economy.

11:46.288 --> 11:47.566
<font color="#80ff80">SHARZA:</font> That is true.

11:47.590 --> 11:50.502
<font color="#80ff80">ELIZABETH:</font> If we could get a
sense of how many schools

11:50.526 --> 11:53.672
we're talking about,
that would be helpful.

11:53.696 --> 11:54.840
That could be quite a...

11:54.864 --> 11:56.708
<font color="#80ffff">(CRYING)</font> Matt Mahoney! Matt Mahoney!

11:56.732 --> 11:59.144
I know him! Please!

11:59.168 --> 12:01.012
Please, please, Matt Mahoney!

12:01.036 --> 12:02.247
I know him. Authorized personnel only.

12:02.271 --> 12:03.682
Please. Please.
Move away from the gate.

12:03.706 --> 12:06.407
Matt Mahoney! <font color="#80ffff">(SPEAKING PASHTO)</font>
Farhana?

12:09.411 --> 12:12.124
<font color="#80ffff">(GATE BUZZES)</font>

12:12.148 --> 12:13.859
Are you okay?

